Question 1

Abstract

Growing trends in global greenhouse gas emissions contribute heavily to the warming of the Earth. Comprised of the greenhouse gas emissions is Carbon Dioxide (CO2) which is emitted through the burning of fossil fuels, and Nitrous Oxide (N2O) which is primarily produced through agricultural production and land managment. As these Greenhouse gas emissions grow into the composition of our atmosphere, the Earths Ozone layer deterioates leading to the warming of the planets climate. Compariatively, studies done on the compund Nitrous Oxide reveal that one pound of Nitrous Oxide warms the atmosphere around 300 times as much as Carbon dioxide over a 100 year life-span. Along with these studies, found that most Nitrous Oxide emissions amount from Land and Agricultural management.**

In this study we will be analyzing the total greenhouse gas emissions of Nitrous Oxide and Carbon Dioxide, and if those emissions correlate to a countrys GDP and Population, as well as how the total emissions compare within global regions. To produce our findings, we will be using data from the Our World in Data organization, which gives us information on a country and their emissions for Carbon Dioxide and Nitrous Oxide, along with their population, GDP, and regions of the Americas, Eurpoe, Asia, and the Middle East.**

Image 1.Photo of Emissions. The New York Times, https://www.nytimes.com/. Accessed 19 Sept.2023.

Question 4

Conclusion

From this study, we can definatively say that the total Greenhouse gas emissions produced across countries correlate strongly with that countrys GDP, and Population. Fromn this we can conclude that countries with strong economies, whore more likely to be industralized and have more technology produce more Greenhosue gas emissions. Countries that have higher populations produce more emissions as they have more capita to do so. ALong with that, studying total Greenhouse gas emissions across Regions suggests that the Americas and Asia/Pacific produce the most greenhouse gases out of the four regions. Future reseach would suggest how to cut back on Greenhouse gas emmisions, and the potential rise in Nitrous Oxide emissions.
